<p>In NYC, working commuters comprise the main flow of population among boroughs, and this flow changes over time [
 <xref rid="pcbi.1005201.ref026" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>]. Accordingly, we formulated the connections between locations based on commuter flow patterns. Commuter flows are much lower at night on weekdays as well as during the weekend [
 <xref rid="pcbi.1005201.ref026" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>]; therefore, for these low-flow time periods, we set 
 <italic>c</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>ij</italic>
 </sub> to 0 (for all 
 <italic>i</italic>≠
 <italic>j</italic>) and 
 <italic>c</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>ii</italic>
 </sub> to 1, which reduces the network model to a simple SIRS construct for each locale. During weekday daytime when mass work commute is in effect, we computed 
 <italic>c</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>ij</italic>
 </sub> using the following formula: 
